tinguish themselves from Europeans, for middle-class authors to assert their class privileges, for men to claim superiority over women in the kitchen, and for lesbian authors to insert themselves into the heteronormative economy of culinary culture. A Taste of Power engages in close reading of a wide variety of sources and genres to uncover the intersections of food, politics, and privilege in American culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCookbooksxSocial aspectsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aCookbooksxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCooking, AmericanxHistory. 0aFood habitsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aFood habitszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFoodxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aFoodxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520960602423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520960602.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles